The “Caterpillar Club” lapel badge was worn by members of an informal, but perhaps the most exclusive, club in the world: pilots who had successfully used a parachute to escape a doomed aircraft. The one my father had was not his, but was given to him by one of the pilots in the South African Air Force (SAAF) 2 Squadron, in recognition of the fact that the parachute which saved that pilot’s life had been packed by my father. As a technician in the 2 Squadron ground crew in the Korean War in 1951, my father was in charge of...